<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>MTH 406: Generalized eigenspaces</title>

  <introduction>
  <p>
    Suppose that <m>T:V \to V</m> is an operator with minimal polynomial 
    <m>p(x)=(x-\lambda)^k q(x)</m> with <m>q(\lambda)\neq 0</m>. Then <m>\lambda</m> is
    an eigenvalue and
  </p>

  <me>
    G_\lambda = \nul((T-\lambda I)^k)
  </me>

  <p>
    is called the <em>generalized eigenspace</em>. An element <m>\vvec</m> in
    <m>G_\lambda</m> is called a <em>generalized eigenvector</em>.
  </p>

  </introduction>
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>We will first show that generalized eigenspaces associated to
      different eigenvalues intersect only in the zero vector.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> is a generalized eigenvector with
        eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>. Explain why <m>(T-\lambda I)^k\vvec = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
    
    <task workspace="0.5in">
      <p>
        What can you conclude about the annihilating polynomial <m>p_\vvec</m>?
      </p>
    </task>
    
    <task workspace="0.5in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\lambda</m> and <m>\mu</m> are two distinct eigenvalues. Use
        these observations to explain why <m>G_\lambda \cap G_\mu = \{0\}</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\dim V = 4</m> and <m>V_1</m> and <m>V_2</m>
        are subspaces of 
        <m>V</m> with <m>\dim V_1 = 3</m> and <m>\dim V_2 =
        2</m>. Then there are bases 
        <m>\{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3\}</m> for <m>V_1</m> and 
        <m>\{\vvec_4,\vvec_5\}</m> for <m>V_2</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Explain why the set
        <me>
          \{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3,\vvec_4,\vvec_5\}
        </me>
        is linearly dependent.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Use this fact to show that <m>V_1 \cap V_2 \neq \{0\}</m>.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>p(x)=(x-2)^3(x-4)^2</m>. If <m>\wvec</m> is in
        <m>\range((T-4I)^2)</m>, explain why <m>(T-2I)^3(\wvec) = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Explain why <m>\range((T-4I)^2) \subset \nul((T-2I)^3) = G_2</m> and
        hence <m>\dim \range((T-4I)^2) \leq \dim G_2</m>.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Explain why
      <me>
        \dim G_4 + \dim \range((T-4I)^2) = \dim V.
      </me>
      </p>
    </task>

    <task>
      <p>
        Explain why
      <me>
        \dim G_4 + \dim G_2 \geq \dim V.
      </me>
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Since <m>G_4 \cap G_2 = \{0\}</m>, explain why 
        <m>\dim G_4 + \dim G_2 = \dim V</m>.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Explain why <m>G_4 \oplus G_2 = V</m>.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Explain why both <m>G_4</m> and <m>G_2</m> are <m>T</m>-invariant.
      </p>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        If <m>\bcal</m> is a basis for <m>G_4</m> and <m>\ccal</m> is
        a basis for <m>G_2</m>, 
        then <m>\dcal=\bcal\cup\ccal</m> is a basis for
        <m>V</m>. Explain why 
      <me>
        \coords{T}{\dcal,\dcal} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
        \coords{T}{\bcal,\bcal} &amp; \zerovec \\
        \zerovec &amp; \coords{T}{\ccal,\ccal}
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
    <conclusion>
      <p>
        What you have found here is generally true: If the minimal polynomial
      <me>
        p(x) =
        (x-\lambda_1)^{k_1}(x-\lambda_2)^{k_2}\ldots(x-\lambda_m)^{k_m},
      </me>,
        then
      <me>
        V = G_{\lambda_1} \oplus G_{\lambda_2} \oplus \ldots \oplus
        G_{\lambda_m}
      </me>
        and there is a basis for <m>V</m> such that the matrix representing <m>T</m>
        is a block matrix where the blocks on the diagonal are
        representations of <m>T|_{G_{\lambda_j}}</m>.
      </p>
    </conclusion>
</worksheet>
